WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.190
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:04.190 --> 00:00:07.960
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Of course
you all know Diana's books,

00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:09.340
or you wouldn't be here.

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:11.610
But let me say just
a few words about her

00:00:11.610 --> 00:00:15.070
and her remarkably original novels.

00:00:15.070 --> 00:00:18.630
They're a bit science fiction,
a lot historical fiction,

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:22.190
and they're all infused with
fantasy, military fiction,

00:00:22.190 --> 00:00:25.490
and a very appealing
dose of romance.

00:00:26.510 --> 00:00:31.840
A novel by Diana is a
genre all to itself.

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:35.630
And that unique approach to
large canvas, big-brained,

00:00:35.630 --> 00:00:42.320
openhearted storytelling has won
her millions of readers worldwide.

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:46.860
She's an Arizona native, part Anglo
American -- thank you, [inaudible],

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:51.500
yes, [laughter] part
Mexican American.

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:54.150
She has a bachelors
degree in zoology,

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:59.040
a masters in marine biology,
and a PhD in animal behavior,

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:00.700
as well as being an expert

00:01:00.700 --> 00:01:04.610
in scientific computation
and micro-computing.

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:07.100
But don't let that scare you.

00:01:08.270 --> 00:01:10.220
[Laughter] She has also
spent her early career

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:15.950
as a comic book scriptwriter,
and in many ways, she is a woman

00:01:15.950 --> 00:01:19.990
for all seasons, and
a writer for all ages.

00:01:19.990 --> 00:01:25.490
As the reviewers have said Diana
writes books that sell like crazy,

00:01:25.490 --> 00:01:29.730
and have gathered devoted readers
from every corner of fandom.

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:33.070
By several reckonings, the
"Outlander" series has sold

00:01:33.070 --> 00:01:39.340
about 28 million books -- I
had 25, but she corrected me,

00:01:39.340 --> 00:01:43.220
[laughter] since Diana's first
novel was published in 1991.

00:01:43.220 --> 00:01:48.470
The series has been translated
into 43 different languages.

00:01:48.470 --> 00:01:52.790
You all know the titles,
"Dragonfly in Amber," "Voyager,"

00:01:52.790 --> 00:01:56.710
"The Scottish Prisoner," "The Fiery
Cross," "An Echo in the Bone,"

00:01:56.710 --> 00:02:00.260
"Written in my Own Heart's
Blood," just to mention a few.

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:02.830
They have all been New
York Times bestsellers,

00:02:02.830 --> 00:02:07.350
they have won many prizes, and
they have been called "breakneck,"

00:02:07.350 --> 00:02:10.640
"rip-roaring," and,
"totally addictive."

00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:14.200
At the end of the talk, you'll have
a chance to pose questions to Diana

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:17.890
at one of the microphones
you see set up in the aisles.

00:02:17.890 --> 00:02:20.360
So save up your thoughts and ideas.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:23.660
I need to tell you, though, you
will be on camera and archived

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:28.540
in the Library of Congress into
perpetuity, [laughter] so make

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.890
that question a smart one.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:35.580 position:56%
[Laughter] You'll also have a
chance to have Diana sign your books

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:40.400
at her 1:00 signing session
down on the lower level.

00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:44.510
So without further adieu, please
welcome our author of the moment.

00:02:44.510 --> 00:03:04.250
[ Applause ]

00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:05.550
&gt;&gt; Diana Gabaldon:
Well, thank you, Robert.

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:06.850
I'm going to remember "big-brained,

00:03:06.850 --> 00:03:10.710
open-hearted storytelling"
for my next cover blurb.

00:03:10.710 --> 00:03:13.210 position:56%
Thank you so much to the organizers,

00:03:13.210 --> 00:03:15.530
and to all of the wonderful
volunteers who have kept me

00:03:15.530 --> 00:03:17.350
from getting lost this morning,

00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:20.130
or at least have recovered
me when I was lost.

00:03:20.130 --> 00:03:24.090
And thank you to all of you
who could just as easily be

00:03:24.090 --> 00:03:26.160
at home washing your
cars or something.

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:28.360 position:56%
I'm glad you came to see me instead.

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:32.870
Back in the day, when I would go
out at night to do events and talk

00:03:32.870 --> 00:03:34.820
to people, my husband
would say to me, "Well,

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:37.250
doesn't it bother you having
to go out and talk to all

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:39.100
of these totally strange people?"

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:44.520
I think he meant "total strangers,"
but [laughter] I said, "Well, no."

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:46.590
I said, "You know, I've
been a university professor

00:03:46.590 --> 00:03:50.270
for a long time, I'm kind of
used to talking to large crowds."

00:03:50.270 --> 00:03:54.210 position:56%
And I said, "If I can keep people
awake at 8:00 in the morning talking

00:03:54.210 --> 00:03:57.990
about human anatomy and physiology,
I can probably keep them awake

00:03:57.990 --> 00:04:02.110
at 8:00 in the evening if they
came on purpose to hear me."

00:04:02.110 --> 00:04:06.130
Back in the day, I would tell very
large crowds, maybe 400 or so,

00:04:06.130 --> 00:04:08.320
because human anatomy
and physiology,

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:11.020
one of my classes, was
a very popular one.

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:13.250
Everybody took it as
a science elective,

00:04:13.250 --> 00:04:15.890 position:56%
including the football team, because
they thought it would be easy.

00:04:15.890 --> 00:04:18.360
I mean, how hard can it
be; count your fingers.

00:04:18.360 --> 00:04:21.430
[Laughs] But anyway, they would
all show up in the morning,

00:04:21.430 --> 00:04:24.650
it was an early class, and
they'd all sit in the front row,

00:04:24.650 --> 00:04:28.550
sound asleep, these large
inanimate blobs of flesh.

00:04:31.030 --> 00:04:33.090
[Laughter] And I would be
standing at a podium like this.

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:36.910
So I would step up and say,
"This morning, gentlemen,

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:39.590
we're going to discuss the
history of contraception."

00:04:39.590 --> 00:04:42.630
And they would all start blinking.

00:04:42.630 --> 00:04:45.870
[Laughing] See, "In days of
old when nights were bold

00:04:45.870 --> 00:04:50.410 position:56%
and condoms not invented, they
wrapped old socks around their cocks

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:51.860
and babies were prevented."

00:04:51.860 --> 00:04:54.510
[Laughter]

00:04:54.510 --> 00:04:59.670
[ Applause ]

00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:02.880
Yes. Well, it worked on
the football players, too.

00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:06.770
[Laughter] No; people always say
to me, "Well, how did you get

00:05:06.770 --> 00:05:08.730
from being a scientist, you
know, with all these degrees

00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:10.030
and things to being a novelist?"

00:05:10.030 --> 00:05:11.480
And I said, "Well,
easy, I wrote a book.

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:14.390
I mean, they don't make
you get a license."

00:05:14.390 --> 00:05:18.280
[Laughter] No; but what they
actually mean is well science seems

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:20.480
all cold, and clinical,
and orderly and tidy,

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:22.790
and white-coded, and,
you know, cold.

00:05:22.790 --> 00:05:24.780
And writing, you know,
it's this creative thing,

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:26.200
it must be all wonderful,
and colorful,

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:27.950
and warm and fuzzy and so forth.

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:29.370
And I'd say, "Well."

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:34.890 position:56%
No; the thing is science and art
both are two sides of the same coin.

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:37.410
They both rest on the same
thing, which is the ability

00:05:37.410 --> 00:05:40.630
to perceive patterns and
draw patterns out of chaos.

00:05:40.630 --> 00:05:45.140 position:56%
When you do science, you define
your chaos by the choice of subject,

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:48.470 position:56%
you know, your organism, your
ecosystem, whatever you're studying.

00:05:48.470 --> 00:05:51.500
And then within that, you try to
define and pick out the patterns

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:53.200
and explicate them to people.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:56.240
Same thing when you do a novel,
then you're defining your chaos

00:05:56.240 --> 00:05:58.700
by the subject that you
choose, or the genre,

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:00.940
but also you include
your own internal chaos

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:02.320
as part of that subject.

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:04.830
And you try to make the
patterns equivalent.

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:07.430
Well, in science, you
come up with a hypothesis.

00:06:07.430 --> 00:06:09.910
You say, "I think this is
what's happening in my system,"

00:06:09.910 --> 00:06:12.620
and then you try to support
it by means of experiment.

00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:16.750 position:56%
Well, your novel is your hypothesis,
and your experiment is the audience.

00:06:16.750 --> 00:06:18.710 position:56%
So you release it upon your audience

00:06:18.710 --> 00:06:21.740
and you see whether they see
the same patterns you do, which,

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:24.850
you know, evidently
you do, so thanks.

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:28.800 position:56%
[Laughter] But as to how I got here,
well, I've known since about the age

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:30.920
of eight that I was
meant to be a novelist.

00:06:30.920 --> 00:06:34.450
This was the age at which I
realized that people write books,

00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:37.620
that they don't just pop out
of the shelves like, you know,

00:06:37.620 --> 00:06:39.450
toilet paper in the grocery store.

00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:44.120
And so I said, "Well, yes, I
think that's what I should do.

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:47.770 position:56%
I was actually having a conversation
with God about it one day.

00:06:47.770 --> 00:06:50.070
I was raised as a Catholic
and they told us, you know,

00:06:50.070 --> 00:06:52.470
it's not just to organize prayers,
you know, you should talk to God

00:06:52.470 --> 00:06:53.770
about your life and so forth."

00:06:53.770 --> 00:06:55.370
So at the age of eight,
I was kind of doing that.

00:06:55.370 --> 00:06:58.670
We were driving somewhere with
my parents, and I was looking

00:06:58.670 --> 00:06:59.970
at the clouds and so forth.

00:06:59.970 --> 00:07:01.270
And, you know, I was
just talking to God.

00:07:01.270 --> 00:07:04.410
Anyway, so you know, "I'm thinking
I kind of want to write books,

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:06.370
you know, that would
kind of lift people up."

00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:09.600
That was my best description
of escape fiction, you know,

00:07:09.600 --> 00:07:12.040
take a story that would lift
people out of themselves

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:13.450
and give them a new experience.

00:07:13.450 --> 00:07:15.540
Anyway, God said, "Yes; I
think that's a good idea."

00:07:15.540 --> 00:07:19.070
So, you know, [laughter] I
kind of -- people said, "Well,

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:22.340
how did you find the nerve, you
know, to do this," and I said,

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:25.400
"I was supposed to do this;
that's not a problem."

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:28.750
But of course, the problem is
always how, because when you set

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:31.960
out to write a book,
there are no road maps.

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:37.050
I was once in Germany
doing a book tour.

00:07:37.050 --> 00:07:39.050
And the publisher, and the
publicist, and, you know,

00:07:39.050 --> 00:07:41.260
all these news people took
me out to lunch together.

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:43.110
And they started asking,
"Well, how did you do this?

00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:44.880
How did you write your novel?"

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:47.690
And so I explained to them what
I'm about to explain to you.

00:07:47.690 --> 00:07:49.060
And they were all shocked.

00:07:49.060 --> 00:07:51.770
You know, they said, "No one in
Germany would dream of trying

00:07:51.770 --> 00:07:55.120
to write a novel without first
getting a PhD in literature."

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:57.960
And I said, "That's probably
why two-thirds of the authors

00:07:57.960 --> 00:08:00.680
in your catalogue are Americans."

00:08:02.990 --> 00:08:05.270
[Laughter] I did not actually say
that because I have better manners,

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:07.930
but, you know, that's
what I thought.

00:08:07.930 --> 00:08:10.800 position:56%
[Laughter] Anyway, the thing is that
anyone who writes a novel is going

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:12.320
to kind of figure it
out for themselves.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:14.790
You know, if you want to be
dentist, or a lawyer, or a doctor,

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:17.760
or something, there is a set
curriculum that you take.

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:19.650
You have to enroll in
this particular school,

00:08:19.650 --> 00:08:21.620
you have to take these
particular classes,

00:08:21.620 --> 00:08:23.880
you pass these particular
formal exams,

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:26.330
and they give you a certificate
that says, "Now you are allowed

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:28.010
to be a doctor," or whatever.

00:08:28.010 --> 00:08:29.740
Okay; you don't need
permission to be a novelist.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:31.050
This is the good thing.

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:33.870
The bad thing is that there
are no rules to follow either.

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:37.800
And people always have their
own individual take on it.

00:08:37.800 --> 00:08:40.710
I don't know a single
author who just sat down

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:42.300
and became an author overnight.

00:08:42.300 --> 00:08:46.050
Most of us have had very checkered
background in one way or another.

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:49.660
I don't know if you're
familiar with Ian Rankin.

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:51.850
He's a Scottish author,
very, very good,

00:08:51.850 --> 00:08:53.820
one of my favorites,
and a good friend, yes.

00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:57.030
But before I knew him personally,
I was reading his books,

00:08:57.030 --> 00:08:58.730
and I would read the
little bio in the back,

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:01.270
and it would always give
his previous occupations

00:09:01.270 --> 00:09:04.240
as including tax collector
and swine herd.

00:09:04.240 --> 00:09:06.930
And [laughter] so when I
finally met him, I said, "Well,

00:09:06.930 --> 00:09:08.370
I have to ask Ian what
is it about --

00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:09.970
how did you get to
come a swine herd?

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:11.550
I don't care how you
got to be a novelist,

00:09:11.550 --> 00:09:12.850
I want to hear about the pigs."

00:09:12.850 --> 00:09:15.900
And he said that well
he was younger,

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:18.750
he and his wife had gotten
jobs as domestic servants

00:09:18.750 --> 00:09:20.650
on a French winery estate.

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:23.870
And his wife took care of
the interior domestic things,

00:09:23.870 --> 00:09:26.220
and he took care of
the outside things,

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:28.510
including slopping the
hogs, and so forth.

00:09:28.510 --> 00:09:30.690
And he said that it was a
very old-fashioned estate.

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:33.350
When they did the harvest, they
actually did in fact strip off

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:35.860
and stomp the grapes and
everyone got very drunk.

00:09:35.860 --> 00:09:39.730
And he said so they did that,
and consequently everyone went

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:41.390
to sleep it off including him.

00:09:41.390 --> 00:09:42.930
Well, when he got up
several hours later,

00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:45.380
he realized that he had
not yet fed the hogs.

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:48.810
And so he went out and
he found a large tub full

00:09:48.810 --> 00:09:52.150
of the discarded wine -- or
grape skins from the stomping.

00:09:52.150 --> 00:09:54.510
And so he tossed these into
the pigs' trough, and the pigs,

00:09:54.510 --> 00:09:55.940
of course, went after them.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:59.380
What he hadn't realized was that
the grape skins had been standing

00:09:59.380 --> 00:10:01.110
in the sun for several hours,

00:10:01.110 --> 00:10:02.870
and the pigs all died
of alcohol poisoning.

00:10:02.870 --> 00:10:04.170
[Gasping] Yes.

00:10:04.170 --> 00:10:07.320
[Laughs] He said that that was the
end of his career as a swine herd,

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:08.870
so I thought I'd better
write novels.

00:10:08.870 --> 00:10:10.170
[Laughter] Yes.

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:13.390
Well, luckily, none of my
previous careers have come to quite

00:10:13.390 --> 00:10:17.400
such a dramatic conclusion,
but I have had quite a few --

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:20.080
let me see, I had the
post-doc appointment

00:10:20.080 --> 00:10:22.140
where my job was to
butcher sea birds.

00:10:22.140 --> 00:10:23.450 position:56%
Luckily, I didn't have to kill them,

00:10:23.450 --> 00:10:26.060
they came pre-killed
from Canada and frozen.

00:10:26.060 --> 00:10:29.130
But it was my job to take
something like a genet --

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:31.580
genets are these big diving
birds that have a wing spread

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:34.970
of about six feet, and they
dive from about 50 feet up.

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:37.690
Consequently, their heads
are made of solid concrete

00:10:37.690 --> 00:10:39.500
because they strike
the water that way.

00:10:39.500 --> 00:10:42.970
And so I was supposed to reduce
all of these different birds

00:10:42.970 --> 00:10:46.200
to 15 different body components,
which I could then analyze

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:48.610
for their protein,
water, and fat content.

00:10:48.610 --> 00:10:51.430
Just don't ask why;
but that was my job.

00:10:51.430 --> 00:10:54.630
Anyway, I learned to
pluck and reduce a genet

00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:56.160
in about three hours flat.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:59.000
But the hard part was the head
because you had to use the hammer

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.830
and chisel, you know, to break
the skull and pour the brain out,

00:11:01.830 --> 00:11:04.460
which was part of the
components that we wanted.

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:06.910
That was probably my
most disgusting job.

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:10.890
I couldn't eat fried chicken
for a year after that.

00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:13.400
[Laughter] The next one
was a little easier.

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:17.260
I was a post-doc at UCLA replacing
a scientist on sabbatical.

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:20.030
So I took over his lab, and
his six graduate students,

00:11:20.030 --> 00:11:23.260
and two Russian scientists
who were studying with him.

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:27.860
And after the Russians left,
the next day an FBI agent showed

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:32.300 position:56%
up in my office, two of them, with
a little warrant badge and so forth.

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:35.080
And one of them dramatically
introduced himself

00:11:35.080 --> 00:11:37.090
as Special Agent Justice.

00:11:37.090 --> 00:11:38.390
And I said, "Of course, you are."

00:11:38.390 --> 00:11:42.290
[Laughter] That actually turned
out to be his real last name.

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:48.100
But anyway they wanted to interview
me about this particular Russian.

00:11:48.100 --> 00:11:50.960
And I told them about
him, and I said, "Look,

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:54.730
if this gentleman is
the best the KBG can do,

00:11:54.730 --> 00:11:56.330
we have nothing to worry about."

00:11:56.330 --> 00:12:01.170
[Laughter] But then I mentioned the
second Russian, and they said, "Oh,

00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:02.470
we didn't know about him."

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:04.710
And I said, "Maybe we do have
something to worry about."

00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:08.390
But anyway, it was a more
interesting job in that

00:12:08.390 --> 00:12:12.380 position:56%
in that one what I had to do was
take high-speed motion picture films

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:13.850
of boxfish.

00:12:13.850 --> 00:12:17.300
And the reason we were doing this
is because -- you may know this,

00:12:17.300 --> 00:12:19.890
those of you who are runners and
so forth, but the more you run

00:12:19.890 --> 00:12:22.310
or the more you exercise,
the more oxygen you use.

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:24.860
So if you take a person or
an animal and you put them

00:12:24.860 --> 00:12:27.920
in a sealed compartment with,
you know, a set amount of oxygen

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:30.130
and you make them exercise
faster and faster,

00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:31.900
their oxygen consumption goes up,

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:34.100
the amount of oxygen
in the tank goes down.

00:12:34.100 --> 00:12:37.500
And so you get this nice
45-degree angle graph, you know,

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:39.410
more oxygen, more exercise.

00:12:39.410 --> 00:12:41.240
Well, boxfish don't do that.

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:44.810
A boxfish, in case you have never
seen one, is very aptly named,

00:12:44.810 --> 00:12:48.080
it's a little box of,
you know, hard shell.

00:12:48.080 --> 00:12:50.450
And their fins are
just on the outside.

00:12:50.450 --> 00:12:52.880
They're not like regular
fish where they swim

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:57.330
in this [inaudible] form motion,
they have a strachae form motion

00:12:57.330 --> 00:12:58.920
because they are strachiadae.

00:12:58.920 --> 00:13:02.650
So they swim like this, and
their little tail goes like that.

00:13:02.650 --> 00:13:04.750
But that's all the
maneuvering they can do.

00:13:04.750 --> 00:13:08.350
And the funny thing about them is
if you make a boxfish exercise,

00:13:08.350 --> 00:13:12.120 position:56%
they will go faster, and faster, and
faster, looking agitated as they do.

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:15.400
And they use more and
more oxygen up to a point.

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:18.960
And then they go faster and faster,
but they don't use anymore oxygen.

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:20.610
And so we said, "How
are they doing that?

00:13:20.610 --> 00:13:21.910
This is really cool."

00:13:21.910 --> 00:13:23.310
Yes; so the person I was working

00:13:23.310 --> 00:13:26.820
with had several hypotheses
to account for that.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:29.550
But the first one of those was
maybe they're doing what people do.

00:13:29.550 --> 00:13:32.000
You know, when you walk faster
and faster, at some point,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.290
you shift into a run
because that's more efficient

00:13:34.290 --> 00:13:35.590
for the speed you're going.

00:13:35.590 --> 00:13:37.890
And at that point, your
oxygen use will drop slightly;

00:13:37.890 --> 00:13:39.460
goes back up if you keep running.

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:43.260
But we were thinking maybe these
guys are doing something special

00:13:43.260 --> 00:13:44.560
with their fins.

00:13:44.560 --> 00:13:47.590
So I was having to do
high-speed motion pictures.

00:13:47.590 --> 00:13:51.680
Well, this was back in
the 1980s, the late 1980s.

00:13:51.680 --> 00:13:55.230
Consequently, I had to shoot
my film, and then take it

00:13:55.230 --> 00:13:58.300
to the CBS TV Studio
to have it processed.

00:13:58.300 --> 00:14:00.400
We talked them into it
as a public service.

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:03.490
So you know, I would go down
behind the Johnny Carson Show stage

00:14:03.490 --> 00:14:06.460
and give them my fish films,
and then I would go back

00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:07.760
and pick them up the next day.

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:10.130 position:56%
It was an interesting place to work.

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:12.230
Also it was -- we lived in Burbank,

00:14:12.230 --> 00:14:16.560 position:56%
and this is when I started writing
Walt Disney comic books on the side.

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:19.230
I'd been reading comic books
since I was three years old;

00:14:19.230 --> 00:14:21.070
that's how my mother
taught me to read.

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:22.560
And I kept on reading them.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:24.920
And while I was working at
UCLA, I had picked up one

00:14:24.920 --> 00:14:27.520
at the grocery store, and I
said, "Well, this is pretty bad,

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:29.160
I bet I could do better myself."

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:32.950
And such was my state of mind that
I found out the name of the editor

00:14:32.950 --> 00:14:36.070
who handled that line and I wrote
him this very rude letter saying,

00:14:36.070 --> 00:14:40.040
"Dear Sir, I have been reading
your comic books for 25 years.

00:14:40.040 --> 00:14:41.620
They've been getting
worse and worse."

00:14:41.620 --> 00:14:44.280
I said, "I'm not sure that
I could do better myself,

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:45.600
but I'd like to try."

00:14:45.600 --> 00:14:47.820
And luckily, I hit a man
named Dell O'Connell,

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:51.360
who was a gentleman
with a sense of humor.

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:52.930 position:56%
He wrote back and said, "Okay, try."

00:14:52.930 --> 00:14:54.610
And he sent along a format

00:14:54.610 --> 00:14:57.460
so I could see what shape
the manuscript should be.

00:14:57.460 --> 00:14:58.760
So I wrote him a story.

00:14:58.760 --> 00:15:01.420
He didn't buy it, but he did
something much more valuable,

00:15:01.420 --> 00:15:02.970
he told me what was wrong with it.

00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:06.340
So he did buy my second story and
he continued to buy my stories

00:15:06.340 --> 00:15:09.370
for another 18 months, at the
end of which the powers that be

00:15:09.370 --> 00:15:12.710
at Disney said, "We've got 40 years
of Carl Barks scripts in our file;

00:15:12.710 --> 00:15:14.010
why are we buying new ones?"

00:15:14.010 --> 00:15:15.520
And they stopped buying new ones.

00:15:15.520 --> 00:15:17.530
But so that was my
short-lived comic book career.

00:15:17.530 --> 00:15:21.520
But I still get a dozen or so
stories out of it, which was good

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:23.910
when I contrast with
what I was doing at work.

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:28.360 position:56%
Anyway, I had to build a water
tunnel and make the fish swim in it.

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:30.030
It has a fan at one end.

00:15:30.030 --> 00:15:33.530
And fish will normally face into
a current, so it was not a problem

00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:35.050
to get them going in
the right direction.

00:15:35.050 --> 00:15:37.340 position:56%
But you would turn on the fan and
they would start swimming like this,

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:38.700
and you'd turn it up, and
they'd swim like this.

00:15:38.700 --> 00:15:40.810
And then you turn it up,
and they'd be going --

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:42.110
and finally they'd be
going [makes sounds].

00:15:42.110 --> 00:15:45.320 position:56%
And they just fall over backwards,
in which you would instantly turn it

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:48.130
out and pull them out with a net
and take them off to recover.

00:15:48.130 --> 00:15:49.990
You know, we were not killing them.

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:52.390
And then, you know, you would
process the film and so forth.

00:15:52.390 --> 00:15:55.720
So that's what I spent
another few years doing.

00:15:55.720 --> 00:15:59.250
But at the age of 35, I
said to myself, "Well,

00:15:59.250 --> 00:16:01.290
you know, Mozart was dead at 36.

00:16:01.290 --> 00:16:04.050
If you want to write a book,
maybe you should get started."

00:16:04.050 --> 00:16:06.120
And so I said, "Okay;
on my next birthday,

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:07.960
I will begin writing a book."

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:12.950
I didn't -- I had to this point,
written all kinds of things.

00:16:12.950 --> 00:16:15.250
I'd written, you know,
doctoral dissertations.

00:16:15.250 --> 00:16:20.830
My PhD dissertation was
titled "[Inaudible],"

00:16:20.830 --> 00:16:25.660
or as my husband says,
"Why Birds Build Nests

00:16:25.660 --> 00:16:27.960 position:56%
Where They Do and Who Cares Anyway?"

00:16:30.710 --> 00:16:35.220 position:56%
[Laughter] But, you know, it was a
400-page dissertation, or let's see,

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:38.270
an 800-page monograph on
dietary habits of the birds

00:16:38.270 --> 00:16:39.940
of the Colorado River Valley.

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:44.210
You might notice a trend here,
you know, 400 pages, 800 pages.

00:16:44.210 --> 00:16:48.040
But I also, you know, wrote
a computer documentation.

00:16:48.040 --> 00:16:51.890
I wrote software reviews
for the computer press, and,

00:16:51.890 --> 00:16:54.910
you know, other things like this.

00:16:54.910 --> 00:16:57.000
Back in the day, my
father would say to me,

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.560
"You're such a poor
judge of character.

00:16:58.560 --> 00:17:00.340
You're bound to marry
some bum," he said,

00:17:00.340 --> 00:17:04.080 position:56%
"so be sure you get a good
education to support your children."

00:17:05.760 --> 00:17:10.330
[Laughter] This is how I ended
up with three science degrees.

00:17:10.330 --> 00:17:12.740
But, you know, I still wanted
to write novels and so forth.

00:17:12.740 --> 00:17:16.000
But in the course of my previous
career, I had gotten all kinds

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.260
of experience in writing,
just not writing novels.

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:23.070
I did not marry a bum, I married a
very nice man whom I still have 45

00:17:23.070 --> 00:17:24.870
years later, and -- thank you.

00:17:24.870 --> 00:17:29.320
[ Applause ]

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:33.020
And my husband thanks you.

00:17:33.020 --> 00:17:35.240
[Laughs] But he did
quit work three months

00:17:35.240 --> 00:17:39.280
after our first child was born in
order to start his own business.

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:43.650
And I do have to say that
between an entrepreneur and a bum,

00:17:43.650 --> 00:17:48.280
there's not that much to choose
in terms of financial stability.

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:53.260 position:56%
Now, luckily, his business got going
fairly quickly and did quite well.

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:56.190
But for the first two or three
years, I was our sole support,

00:17:56.190 --> 00:17:59.510
and they don't assistant
biology professors that much.

00:17:59.510 --> 00:18:03.070
So at this point, the need
to earn extra money arose.

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:05.190
And so I said, "Well, what can I
do to earn a little extra money,

00:18:05.190 --> 00:18:07.480
you know, other than
prostitution in the home?"

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:12.150 position:56%
And [laughter] I said, "Well, I
know how to write, I mean, you know,

00:18:12.150 --> 00:18:14.880
I'm grammatical, I know
punctuation, all that.

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:17.890
And I know quite a
lot about computers."

00:18:17.890 --> 00:18:20.890
This happened as an accident when
I was -- all of the, you know,

00:18:20.890 --> 00:18:22.760
things in my life have
happened as accidents,

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:25.470
including meeting my husband; I
met him in the French horn section

00:18:25.470 --> 00:18:28.760
of the Arizona marching band.

00:18:28.760 --> 00:18:31.140
[Laughter] But anyway, in
this particular instance,

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:35.810
the accident had more to
do with my job, that is,

00:18:35.810 --> 00:18:38.510
I was hired at Arizona
State University

00:18:38.510 --> 00:18:41.150
because they had money
allocated for the position.

00:18:41.150 --> 00:18:43.630
But as they said, "We have this
money, but it's soft money.

00:18:43.630 --> 00:18:46.500
If we don't spend it, they'll
take it away, so you're hired."

00:18:46.500 --> 00:18:48.860
And they said, "This is
how government works,

00:18:48.860 --> 00:18:50.870
in case you were wondering."

00:18:50.870 --> 00:18:54.250
And they were saying, "So we
don't actually have anything

00:18:54.250 --> 00:18:55.550
for you to do.

00:18:55.550 --> 00:18:57.790
We would like for you to
develop your own research.

00:18:57.790 --> 00:18:59.840
But while you're doing it,
maybe you could help Bob here

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:01.140
who is the assistant professor

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:03.440
and the assistant director
with his data."

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:06.680
Said, "ob has, you know, ten years'
worth of data in his back room.

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:08.960 position:56%
And you have a computer background,"

00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:12.660
by which they meant I have one
class in Fortran programming.

00:19:12.660 --> 00:19:15.210
[Laughter] But it was one more than
any of them had, and so they said,

00:19:15.210 --> 00:19:17.910
"So you can help Bob get
his data into the computer."

00:19:17.910 --> 00:19:20.020
This was like 1981.

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:22.640
"Macro computers," as they were
called, were just barely coming

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:26.030
into offices and universities at
the time, and they still thought

00:19:26.030 --> 00:19:27.600
that you poured data in the top,

00:19:27.600 --> 00:19:29.250
and then you got reports
out at the bottom.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:32.090
So it was my job how to figure out
how to get the top off the computer

00:19:32.090 --> 00:19:33.390
and get the data into it.

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:38.420
So I spent the next 18 months of
my life writing Fortran programs

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:41.120
to analyze the contents
of bird gizzards.

00:19:41.120 --> 00:19:45.040
There's actually a reason
why I'm telling you this.

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:46.360
There's a reason why
I write long books,

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:47.660
it's because I like digressions.

00:19:47.660 --> 00:19:54.870
But [laughter] anyway at the end
of this 18 months of work I said,

00:19:54.870 --> 00:19:57.620
"There's maybe five other people in
the entire world who are interested

00:19:57.620 --> 00:20:00.620
in bird gizzards, but it would
save each of them 18 months' worth

00:20:00.620 --> 00:20:02.890
of work if they knew about
these programs I've written."

00:20:02.890 --> 00:20:05.400 position:56%
I was thinking, "There must be other
people out there who are, you know,

00:20:05.400 --> 00:20:08.830
employing this new tool,
computers, and doing science.

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:11.740
Why is there no way in
which we can communicate?"

00:20:11.740 --> 00:20:15.330
So I took out a little
ad in the newsletters

00:20:15.330 --> 00:20:17.990
of all the scientific
societies I could find,

00:20:17.990 --> 00:20:19.290
and I explained what I was doing.

00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:21.300
And I said I know there are other
people out there doing this.

00:20:21.300 --> 00:20:22.600
Why won't you write to me?

00:20:22.600 --> 00:20:24.740 position:56%
If there's enough of us, maybe we
can put together a little newsletter

00:20:24.740 --> 00:20:26.040
of our own."

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:28.230
So I got 300 letters in two months.

00:20:28.230 --> 00:20:32.530
And I took these to the director
of my center, and I said, "Well,

00:20:32.530 --> 00:20:34.600
I'm not having any luck
getting money out of the NSF,

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:36.410
but I think I've started
something here.

00:20:36.410 --> 00:20:38.290
Can you front me a little
money from petty cash

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:39.640
and I'll see what I can do?"

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:41.520
So he gave me $250.

00:20:41.520 --> 00:20:45.010
I printed up some brochures and I
took them to the next conference

00:20:45.010 --> 00:20:48.200
that I was going to, and handed
them out on the floor to people.

00:20:48.200 --> 00:20:50.560
Well, I raised enough money
in charter subscriptions

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:54.380 position:56%
to start Science Software Quarterly,
which was a scholarly journal

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:57.570
for scientists who used computers
in their work, which was fun.

00:20:57.570 --> 00:20:59.970
Anyway, I ran that for about eight
years and I developed, you know,

00:20:59.970 --> 00:21:03.290
seminars for an international
group of scientists who wanted

00:21:03.290 --> 00:21:05.800
to come learn about
laboratory automation,

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:07.870
and data acquisition,
and that kind of stuff.

00:21:07.870 --> 00:21:10.470
All of which is just
to explain how it was

00:21:10.470 --> 00:21:12.650
that I had a second
career at the time.

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:15.510
So I was teaching, and I
was a university professor,

00:21:15.510 --> 00:21:17.160
and I was doing my own research,

00:21:17.160 --> 00:21:19.770
but I also developed
this secondary career.

00:21:19.770 --> 00:21:22.500
When the need for extra
money arose, I said, "Okay;

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:24.620
I know about computers
and I can write."

00:21:24.620 --> 00:21:28.440
So I wrote a quick query letter to
Byte, and Info World, and PC Mag,

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:31.610
and I sent it with a copy of
my Science Software Quarterly,

00:21:31.610 --> 00:21:35.470
and a copy of a comic book that
I had done for Walt Disney called

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:38.640
"Nutrition Adventures with
Orange Bird [phonetic]."

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:40.190
And it was a real short query.

00:21:40.190 --> 00:21:43.670
It said, "Dear sirs, as you
can see from the enclosed,

00:21:43.670 --> 00:21:46.140
you won't find anyone who
knows more about scientific

00:21:46.140 --> 00:21:48.940
and technical software than
I do, and at the same time,

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:52.040
can write so as to appeal to
a broad popular audience."

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:54.820
Well, this got immediate results,
and, you know, within a few months,

00:21:54.820 --> 00:21:57.770
I was making as much freelancing
for the computer press as I was

00:21:57.770 --> 00:21:59.530
at the university, which just goes

00:21:59.530 --> 00:22:01.960
to show how badly they
pay assistant professors.

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:05.540
But anyway, at the time, when I
made up my mind to write a book,

00:22:05.540 --> 00:22:09.190
I was 36 years old, I
had two fulltime jobs

00:22:09.190 --> 00:22:11.840
and three children
under the age of six.

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:13.470
So I don't want anyone telling me

00:22:13.470 --> 00:22:16.270
that they don't have
time to write a book.

00:22:16.270 --> 00:22:19.460
[Laughter] If you want to write
a book, you'll make the time.

00:22:19.460 --> 00:22:22.380
I mean, nobody finds time; it's not
just lying around in the street.

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:25.230
Unfortunately, you have to
make it, or you don't have any.

00:22:25.230 --> 00:22:27.190
But, you know, the
time and so forth.

00:22:27.190 --> 00:22:31.420
And the question is always -- says
a lot of people, especially women,

00:22:31.420 --> 00:22:34.630
they said, "I can't justify taking
time away from my family, you know,

00:22:34.630 --> 00:22:36.330
to be doing something
like writing, you know,

00:22:36.330 --> 00:22:37.950
this frivolous silly thing."

00:22:37.950 --> 00:22:42.330
And my first question is,
"Do you watch television?"

00:22:42.330 --> 00:22:44.740
And I said, "Okay; I do
feel like that's a waste

00:22:44.740 --> 00:22:47.840
of your time because,
you know, it's a choice.

00:22:47.840 --> 00:22:50.300
Why don't you take one of the hours
you would spend watching television

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:52.230
and work on your book?"

00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:54.080
Because it's fairly simple.

00:22:54.080 --> 00:22:57.210
I was talking to Rick Rankin,
one of the new cast members

00:22:57.210 --> 00:22:58.680
for the "Outlander" TV show.

00:22:58.680 --> 00:23:02.230
He was -- oh yes he's very
nice; he's really charming.

00:23:02.230 --> 00:23:04.830
Yes; he sort of walked into
the makeup room, spotted me.

00:23:04.830 --> 00:23:06.130
We had never met before.

00:23:06.130 --> 00:23:08.830
He walked over and kissed me
and I said, "Really, okay."

00:23:08.830 --> 00:23:12.130
Well, [laughter] Scotsmen
are different, yes.

00:23:12.130 --> 00:23:14.040
They all do that, actually.

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:18.200
But anyway, he was talking to me
later about writing and so forth.

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:19.500
And he said, "You know,
I've always wanted

00:23:19.500 --> 00:23:20.800
to write a book, but,
you know, time."

00:23:20.800 --> 00:23:24.230
I said, "Look," I said, "if
you have ten minutes a day,

00:23:24.230 --> 00:23:27.150
and you can do it every
day, you can write a book."

00:23:27.150 --> 00:23:28.770
I said, "Take that
ten minutes and write.

00:23:28.770 --> 00:23:30.850
Okay; if that's all you've
got, that's all you've got.

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:32.150
But do it the next day."

00:23:32.150 --> 00:23:33.710
I said, "If you write
ten minutes every day,

00:23:33.710 --> 00:23:35.670
you will have a book within a year.

00:23:35.670 --> 00:23:37.570
It may not be a big book,
but you'll have a book."

00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:39.810
I said, "If you don't do
that, you won't have a book.

00:23:39.810 --> 00:23:41.110
It's that simple.

00:23:41.110 --> 00:23:42.410
You know, you'll have time.

00:23:42.410 --> 00:23:44.060
It doesn't have to be
a big amount of time."

00:23:44.060 --> 00:23:45.360
Lots of people think, "Oh,

00:23:45.360 --> 00:23:47.500
I can't possibly write unless
I have eight hours a day,

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:50.200
and individual support, and a
room of my own, and, you know,

00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:53.570
everybody is keeping everybody
away from me so that I can write."

00:23:53.570 --> 00:23:55.140
And it kind of doesn't
work that way.

00:23:55.140 --> 00:23:58.490
You know, you write any way
is what it comes down to.

00:23:58.490 --> 00:24:02.350
So anyway, I kind of knew that
because of what else I was doing.

00:24:02.350 --> 00:24:06.940
And so I just involved the
writing into my regular routine.

00:24:06.940 --> 00:24:12.030
But I went immediately to think,
"What am I going to write?"

00:24:12.030 --> 00:24:14.000
And because I read
everything, and lots of it.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.550
And I said, "Well, maybe I should
write a mystery; I love mysteries."

00:24:16.550 --> 00:24:18.570
And I said, "No; mysteries
have plots.

00:24:18.570 --> 00:24:20.030
I'm not sure I can do that."

00:24:20.030 --> 00:24:22.670
And -- [laughter] well I never had.

00:24:22.670 --> 00:24:25.150
And so I said, "Okay; what's
the easiest thing to write?"

00:24:25.150 --> 00:24:26.620
No point making it hard.

00:24:26.620 --> 00:24:27.920
And so I thought, "Well, for me,

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:31.090
maybe a historical novel would
be the easiest thing to write.

00:24:31.090 --> 00:24:33.910
I was a research professor; I
knew my way around a library.

00:24:33.910 --> 00:24:39.170
I said, "It seems easier to look
things up than to make them up."

00:24:39.170 --> 00:24:41.750
And if I turn out that I have no
imagination, I can steal things

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:44.960
from the historical record,"
which actually works pretty well.

00:24:44.960 --> 00:24:47.470
And so I said, "All
right, historical novel;

00:24:47.470 --> 00:24:50.210
where shall I set this," because
I've got no background in history,

00:24:50.210 --> 00:24:52.900
just the six hours of Western
Civilization they make you take

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:54.220
as an undergraduate.

00:24:54.220 --> 00:24:56.790
And so any time would
do as well as another.

00:24:56.790 --> 00:24:59.570
And so I said, "Okay;
let me think about this."

00:24:59.570 --> 00:25:02.180
And so I was thinking, you know,
"15th century Venice, you know,

00:25:02.180 --> 00:25:04.290
American Civil War, what
sounds interesting?"

00:25:04.290 --> 00:25:06.000
Well, in this malleable
frame of mine,

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:10.340
I happened to see a really old Dr.
Who rerun on public television.

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:13.290
And this -- thank you.

00:25:13.290 --> 00:25:14.710
Yes; it was one of
the really old ones.

00:25:14.710 --> 00:25:16.760
It was Patrick Troughton,
the second doctor.

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:20.080
For those of you who may not
be familiar with "Dr. Who,"

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:23.460
it's a really old, really
long-running show done in the UK.

00:25:23.460 --> 00:25:25.580
Originally, it was a kids'
show, but now much more adult.

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:28.860
The thesis, or the
premise of the show is

00:25:28.860 --> 00:25:32.110
that the doctor is a time
lord from the planet Galifre,

00:25:32.110 --> 00:25:34.800
who travels through space
and time having adventures.

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:36.630
And along the way, he
picks up companions

00:25:36.630 --> 00:25:38.580
from different periods
of Earth's history.

00:25:38.580 --> 00:25:39.880
Well, in this particular show,

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:42.960
he had picked up a young
Scotsman from 1745.

00:25:42.960 --> 00:25:44.830
And this was a, you know,
nice looking young man

00:25:44.830 --> 00:25:46.130
who appeared in his kilt.

00:25:46.130 --> 00:25:48.000
And I said, "That's
rather fetching."

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:51.320
[Laughter] And I found
myself still thinking

00:25:51.320 --> 00:25:53.450
about this the next day in church.

00:25:53.450 --> 00:25:58.260
And I said, [laughter] "Well, you
know, you want to write a book,

00:25:58.260 --> 00:25:59.560
it doesn't really matter.

00:25:59.560 --> 00:26:01.710
Fine, let's start there,
Scotland, 18th century."

00:26:01.710 --> 00:26:03.890
So that's where I began,
knowing nothing about Scotland

00:26:03.890 --> 00:26:07.960 position:56%
or the 18th century, having no
plot, no outline, and no characters,

00:26:07.960 --> 00:26:11.380
just the rather vague images
conjured up by the notion of a man

00:26:11.380 --> 00:26:14.860
in a kilt, which is, of course, a
very powerful and compelling image.

00:26:14.860 --> 00:26:20.660
[Laughter] In fact, some
years later, my sixth book,

00:26:20.660 --> 00:26:23.160
which was a very lucky book
for me, it won several awards,

00:26:23.160 --> 00:26:26.800
including the Corine International
Prize for Fiction, which is cool.

00:26:26.800 --> 00:26:28.730
And I got to go to
Germany to accept it.

00:26:28.730 --> 00:26:31.420
Well, while I was there, the
German editor had me interviewed

00:26:31.420 --> 00:26:33.520
by everybody in the German
media from, you know,

00:26:33.520 --> 00:26:35.630
the tabloid newspapers on up.

00:26:35.630 --> 00:26:38.750 position:56%
And toward the end of this very long
week, I was talking to a nice man

00:26:38.750 --> 00:26:40.050
from a literary magazine.

00:26:40.050 --> 00:26:41.500
And he said, "Oh, I've read
all of your work, you know,

00:26:41.500 --> 00:26:43.060
your characters are
so three-dimensional.

00:26:43.060 --> 00:26:44.520
Your narrative drive is tremendous.

00:26:44.520 --> 00:26:46.400
You know, your imagery,
it's just transcendent."

00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:48.180
I'm thinking, "Yes, yes, go on."

00:26:48.180 --> 00:26:52.170
[Laughter] And instead he said,
"There's just this one thing,

00:26:52.170 --> 00:26:57.870 position:56%
I wonder, can you explain to me what
is the appeal of a man in a kilt?"

00:26:57.870 --> 00:27:00.240
[Laughter] Well, he was
a man, and a German.

00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:03.620
And anyway, I was really tired
or might not have said it,

00:27:03.620 --> 00:27:05.420
but I just looked at him
for a minute and I said,

00:27:05.420 --> 00:27:07.020
"I suppose it's the
idea that you could be

00:27:07.020 --> 00:27:09.510
up against a wall with
him in a minute."

00:27:09.510 --> 00:27:21.040
[ Laughter ]

00:27:21.040 --> 00:27:27.100 position:56%
Yes; so that is actually in case
any of you gentlemen were wondering.

00:27:27.100 --> 00:27:30.000
[Laughter] But anyway, a
man in a kilt, as I say.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.580
So that's why I chose Scotland,
and that is why I chose Scotland

00:27:34.580 --> 00:27:37.360
in the 18th century,
you know, there it is.

00:27:37.360 --> 00:27:40.350
[Laughter] So anyway, I went
immediately to the library

00:27:40.350 --> 00:27:42.920
and began looking up
Scotland in the 18th century.

00:27:42.920 --> 00:27:46.400
Now, the only thing I actually knew
about books or writing a novel was

00:27:46.400 --> 00:27:47.720
that it should have conflict.

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:51.030
You know, I had a minor in
English and that was the sole sum

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:53.290 position:56%
of my knowledge from that, conflict.

00:27:53.290 --> 00:27:56.460
And so you don't look for conflict
in Scotland in the 18th century

00:27:56.460 --> 00:27:59.510
for very long without running smack
into [inaudible] Prince Charlie

00:27:59.510 --> 00:28:00.810
and the Jacobite Rebellion.

00:28:00.810 --> 00:28:02.110
And I said, "Well,
that looks like plenty

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:03.800
of conflict, fine, we'll use them."

00:28:03.800 --> 00:28:05.620
And so that's where I began.

00:28:05.620 --> 00:28:09.200
I was just doing research at the
same time as I was writing, and,

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:11.330
you know, just beginning
feeble stabs at writing.

00:28:11.330 --> 00:28:15.080
I was just putting down bits
and pieces of, you know,

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:17.970
just vaguely imagined things
with my man in a kilt.

00:28:17.970 --> 00:28:21.100
And none of those ever made
it into the published book.

00:28:21.100 --> 00:28:23.550
But as I was working with this,
I was thinking, "Well, you know,

00:28:23.550 --> 00:28:25.860
essentially it's Scots
versus English here.

00:28:25.860 --> 00:28:28.930
And I must have a lot of Scotsmen,
of course, for the kilt factor.

00:28:28.930 --> 00:28:31.540
But it would be a good idea
if I had a female character

00:28:31.540 --> 00:28:34.180 position:56%
to play off these guys, you know,
sexual tension, that sort of thing."

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:36.110
I said, "So if I make
her an English woman,

00:28:36.110 --> 00:28:38.120
we will have lots of conflict."

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:41.400
So on the third day of writing,
I introduced this English woman,

00:28:41.400 --> 00:28:43.730
no idea who she was, what she was
doing there, or how she was going

00:28:43.730 --> 00:28:45.280
to carry out on the story.

00:28:45.280 --> 00:28:48.790 position:56%
But I loosed her into a cottage full
of Scotsmen to see what she'd do.

00:28:48.790 --> 00:28:51.040
Well, she walked in,
and they were all seated

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:52.390
around the fire muttering
to each other.

00:28:52.390 --> 00:28:53.690
They turned around, stared at her.

00:28:53.690 --> 00:28:55.250
And I'm thinking, "Why,
does she look funny?

00:28:55.250 --> 00:28:56.550
You know, what's going on here?"

00:28:56.550 --> 00:28:59.320
Anyway, one of them drew
himself up and he said,

00:28:59.320 --> 00:29:03.360
"My name's Dugal McKenzie,
and who are you?"

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:07.380
And she looked up and without my
stopping to think I just typed,

00:29:07.380 --> 00:29:11.400
"My name is Claire Elizabeth
Beecham, and who the hell are you?"

00:29:11.400 --> 00:29:13.730
[Laughter] And I said,
"Okay; you don't sound at all

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:15.430
like an 18th century person."

00:29:15.430 --> 00:29:18.160
So I fought with her in several
pages trying to beat her into shape

00:29:18.160 --> 00:29:20.680
and make her talk like
an 18th century person.

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:22.970
But she wasn't having any,
she just kept making smart ass

00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:24.270
modern remarks.

00:29:24.270 --> 00:29:27.650
And she also took over and
started telling the story herself.

00:29:27.650 --> 00:29:29.230
And I said, "Okay;
I'm not going to fight

00:29:29.230 --> 00:29:30.530
with you all the way
through this book."

00:29:30.530 --> 00:29:31.980
I said, "No one's ever
going to see this.

00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:34.600
It doesn't matter what bizarre
thing I do, go ahead and be modern

00:29:34.600 --> 00:29:36.530
and I'll figure out how
you got there later."

00:29:36.530 --> 00:29:41.300
So it's all her fault that
there's time travel in these books.

00:29:41.300 --> 00:29:43.160
[Laughter] But you know, once
having made that decision,

00:29:43.160 --> 00:29:44.760
well obviously anything else went.

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:49.160
So, you know, while the historical
background is as accurate

00:29:49.160 --> 00:29:50.920 position:56%
as history itself is, which means --

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:54.000
which is to say not
necessarily all the truth,

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.230
but it was all the truth,
it was written down.

00:29:56.230 --> 00:29:58.370
Anyway, the background
is very accurate.

00:29:58.370 --> 00:30:03.180
But part of the art of
immersion in popular fiction is

00:30:03.180 --> 00:30:04.530
by making little connections

00:30:04.530 --> 00:30:07.280
with your readers amongst those
details they can identify with.

00:30:07.280 --> 00:30:09.420
And I can tell you
what, if you are very,

00:30:09.420 --> 00:30:13.320
very good at making the details
of daily life believable,

00:30:13.320 --> 00:30:15.950 position:56%
then your readers will follow you
right over a cliff when you ask them

00:30:15.950 --> 00:30:17.250
to believe in time travel.

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:18.730
[Laughter] That's how you do it.

00:30:18.730 --> 00:30:21.940
So there is a lot of research
involved in these books, but,

00:30:21.940 --> 00:30:24.730
you know, I was a research
professor and that's how it works.

00:30:24.730 --> 00:30:26.240
Well, let's see, how
are we doing for time?

00:30:26.240 --> 00:30:29.100
Okay, we have two minutes before
we start questions and so forth.

00:30:29.100 --> 00:30:32.430 position:56%
So that is just about enough time
to explain how I got from this point

00:30:32.430 --> 00:30:34.070
to actually being published,

00:30:34.070 --> 00:30:37.410
because this was this book I
was never going to show anyone.

00:30:37.410 --> 00:30:41.370
Well, what happened was that
owing to my computer background

00:30:41.370 --> 00:30:44.410
and so forth, I had stumbled
into a group of people called the

00:30:44.410 --> 00:30:45.850
"CompuServe Literary Forum."

00:30:45.850 --> 00:30:48.050
It was just by accident while
I was doing research for one

00:30:48.050 --> 00:30:49.680 position:56%
of the software reviews I was doing.

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:53.130
And this was like a 24-hour
